FAQs
How do I find organizations to join?
You can explore over 500 student-led groups by using Mason360. This platform allows you to browse through various categories, including Registered Student Organizations (RSOs), Club Sports, Fraternity & Sorority Life, and Campus-Wide Organizations.

What is a Registered Student Organization (RSO)?
RSOs are student-led organizations recognized and guided by the Student Involvement Office. These organizations provide diverse opportunities for engagement, help students foster skills for a global workforce, and host social, cultural, and educational events that enhance the campus atmosphere.

How do I search by interest?
You can browse organizations by specific interest categories on Mason360. Categories include Academic, STEM, Student Media, Health & Wellness, Performing & Visual Arts, Religious & Spiritual, and many more. You can also use the "Search Key Words" function on Mason360 to find groups that match your specific interests.

What if I cannot find an organization that fits me?
If you can’t find an organization that meets your needs, you can start your own! The RSO HUB is available to help you through the process of creating a new Registered Student Organization with the support of Student Involvement.

What is the RSO HUB?
The RSO HUB is a one-stop resource destination designed to help club officers and members pursue their goals. It provides essential information on how to start a club, apply for funding, re-register an existing club, and explore officer roles. Note: A George Mason University sign-in is required to access the HUB.

Are student organizations inclusive?
Yes. All student organizations registered with the university are inclusive and welcoming to students of all protected groups. Every organization agrees to adhere to George Mason University policies as well as local, state, and federal laws to ensure a welcoming environment for all students.

Who do I contact if I have questions?
For RSOs, contact the Student Involvement Office.

For Club Sports, contact Mason Recreation staff.

For Fraternities and Sororities, contact Student Involvement and the governing councils.

For Campus-Wide/Department-Sponsored Organizations (DSOs), contact the specific University Department that guides them.

For help starting a new club or managing an existing one, visit the RSO HUB.
